	h2
		b Integers
	h3
		b Defining integers
	p To extend the number line to negative numbers, we define:
	p $$\forall ab \in \mathbb{N} \exists c (a+c=b)$$
	p For any pair of numbers there exists a terms which can be added to one to get the other.
	p For \(1+x=3\) this is another natural number, however for \(3+x=1\) there is no such number.
	p Integers are defined as the solutions for any pair of natural numbers.
	p
		b Integers as ordered pairs
	p Integers can be defined as an ordered pair of natural numbers, where the integer is valued at: \(a-b\).
	p For example \(-1\) could be shown as:
	p $$-1= \{ \{ 0 \},\{0,1\}\}$$
	p $$-1= \{ \{ 5 \},\{5,6\}\}$$

	p $$(a,b)=a-b$$
	p
		b Converting natural numbers to integers
	p Natural numbers can be shown as integers by using:
	p $$(n,0)$$
	p Natural numbers can be converted to integers:
	p $$\{\{a\},\{a,0\}\}$$
	h3
		b Ordering integers
	p Integers are an ordered pair of naturals.
	p $$\{\{x\},\{x,y\}\}$$
	p For example \(-4\) can be:
	p $$\{\{4\},\{4,8\}\}$$
	p $$\{\{0\},\{0,8\}\}$$
	p We extend the ordering to say:
	p $$\{\{x\},\{x,y\}\}\le \{\{s(x)\},\{s(x),y\}\}$$
	p $$\{\{x\},\{x,s(y)\}\}\le \{\{x\},\{x,y\}\}$$
	p So can we define this on an arbitrary pair:
	p $$\{\{a\},\{a,b\}\}\le \{\{c\},\{c,d\}\}$$
	p We know that:
	p $$\{\{a\},\{a,b\}\}=\{\{s(a)\},\{s(a),s(b)\}\}$$
	p And either of:
	p $$\{\{a\},\{a,b\}\}=\{\{0\},\{0,A\}\}$$
	p $$\{\{a\},\{a,b\}\}=\{\{B\},\{B,0\}\}$$
	p $$\{\{a\},\{a,b\}\}=\{\{0\},\{0,0\}\}$$
	p As the latter is a case of either of the other \(2\), we consider only the first \(2\).
	p So we can define:
	p $$\{\{a\},\{a,b\}\}\le \{\{c\},\{c,d\}\}$$
	p As any of:
	p $$1: \{\{0\},\{0,A\}\}\le \{\{0\},\{0,C\}\}$$
	p $$2: \{\{0\},\{0,A\}\}\le \{\{D\},\{D,0\}\}$$
	p $$3: \{\{B\},\{B,0\}\}\le \{\{0\},\{0,C\}\}$$
	p $$4: \{\{B\},\{B,0\}\}\le \{\{D\},\{D,0\}\}$$
	p Case 1:
	p $$\{\{0\},\{0,A\}\}\le \{\{0\},\{0,C\}\}$$
	p Trivial, depends on relative size of \(A\) and \(C\).
	p

	p Case 2:
	p $$\{\{0\},\{0,A\}\}\le \{\{D\},\{D,0\}\}$$
	p We can see that:
	p $$\{\{D\},\{D,A\}\}\le \{\{D\},\{D,0\}\}$$
	p And therefore this holds.
	p

	p Case 3:
	p $$\{\{B\},\{B,0\}\}\le \{\{0\},\{0,C\}\}$$
	p We can see that:
	p $$\{\{B\},\{B,0\}\}\le \{\{B\},\{B,C\}\}$$
	p And therefore this does not hold.
	p
	p Case 4:
	p $$\{\{B\},\{B,0\}\}\le \{\{D\},\{D,0\}\}$$
	p Trivial, like case 1.
	p
